{{Infobox person | name = Donald Roulet | image = https://www.tulsaworld.com/obituaries/localobituaries/donald-roulet/article_d9e5d977-fbdb-58b0-88ab-b4ff9e2cfa82.html | caption = | birth_name = Donald Eugene Roulet | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1936}} | birth_place = [[Beverly Hills]], CA, US | death_date = May 27, 2017 | death_place = Tulsa, OK | nationality = American | occupation = Minister [[Presbyterian Church USA]] | children = 3 }}
'''Donald Eugene Roulet''' was a [[Presbyterian]] [[Minister (religion)|minister]], known for involvement in Civil Rights issues within the [[Presbyterian Church USA]]. Roulet was a founding member of the [[Progressive Religion Coalition of Tulsa]], an organization that advocates for religious tolerance and inclusion.<ref>[http://gtrnews.com/greater-tulsa-reporter/775/BAPresbyterianBoastsUniqueHistory GTR News: "B.A. Presbyterian Boasts Unique History"] July 25, 2005</ref><ref>[http://collegehilltulsa.org/who-are-we/history/ College Hill Presbyterian Church: College Hill History]</ref>
==Ministry== Donald Roulet became minister of the First Presbyterian Church of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]], [[Oklahoma]] in 1963. Through this church, Roulet established community outreach programs in the Tulsa area providing meals to senior citizens, [[Alcoholics Anonymous]] and Food Pantry Programs. Most notably, he started the Chow and [[Obitu|Chatter]] Club, which provides weekly lunch to senior citizens.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SHgCBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA257&lpg=PA257&dq=donald+roulet+broken+arrow&source=bl&ots=M1H5336mSV&sig=sR5XtIgehwAmt-QR85StZsENjMk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QD03VYfIKsKcsAWT-oDwCg&ved=0CCoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=donald%20roulet%20broken%20arrow&f=false "Divided Hearts: The Presbyterian Journey Through Oklahoma."]</ref> He served on all major committees in the Eastern Oklahoma Presbytery, before retiring in 1991.<ref>[http://gtrnews.com/greater-tulsa-reporter/775/BAPresbyterianBoastsUniqueHistory: GTR News: "B.A. Presbyterian Boasts Unique History"] July 25, 2005</ref> Following retirement, he served as the Executive Presbyter of the [[Presbytery of Southern Louisiana]]. Roulet obtained a [[Master of Divinity]] from [[McCormick Theological Seminary]], as well as two Doctoral Degrees in Ministry and Theology.<ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/samaritan-pastor-touches-lives/article_7197b0b4-acd1-5099-acc0-c247e98634ac.html Tulsa World: "Samaritan' Pastor Touches Lives"] February 16, 1991.</ref>
==Personal life== Donald Eugene Roulet was born in 1936 in [[Beverly Hills]], [[California]]. He was a member of the Franco-German [[Roulet family]], a noble family from [[Alsace]]. After graduating from [[Tulsa University]], he married his wife Wyneth in November, 1959. They have three grown children, [[Scott E. Roulet]], a media executive, Michelle and Steven.<ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/samaritan-pastor-touches-lives/article_7197b0b4-acd1-5099-acc0-c247e98634ac.html Tulsa World: "Samaritan Pastor Touches Lives"] February 16, 1991.</ref>
==Honors and awards== Roulet was an Honorary Chaplain for the [[Oklahoma Senate]], and an Honorary [[Mayor]] of the City of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]]. He had also been honored by the Louisiana House of Representatives.
