'''Identity disorder''' in the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders|DSM]], was first listed as a separate diagnosis in version III (1980). In version IV (1994), it was replaced by "[[DSM-IV codes#Additional codes|Identity problem]]", which was not defined as a mental disorder per se, but was listed in a chapter containing problems that might be a focus of clinical attention. Identity disorder was 'downgraded' to Identity problem as research indicated that distress over one's identity is so common that it might very well be considered part of the [[Normality (behavior)|normality]]. In practice, if a person's distress persisted or worsened, an Identity problem would often be succeeded by a diagnosis of an actual disorder, such as a [[mood disorder]] or [[borderline personality disorder]]. In [[DSM-5]] (2013), "Identity problem" was removed.<ref>{{Cite book | first1=Judith L. | last1=Rapoport | first2=Deborah R. | last2=Ismond | title=DSM-IV Training Guide for Diagnosis of Childhood Disorders | year=1996 | page=282 | isbn=978-0876307663 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2AmJH3Iwf2kC&lpg=PA282&pg=PA282#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | first1=James E. | last1=Côté | first2=Charles G. | last2=Levine | title=Identity Formation, Agency, and Culture: A Social Psychological Synthesis | year=2002 | page=155 | isbn=978-1135650049 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cyh5AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP155&pg=PA155#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
